isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.57) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.27. The models intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.28, p < .001, 95% CI [12.98, 14.08]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.40, p = 0.746, 95% CI [-0.91, 0.65]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.20, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.45, S.E. = 0.33, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.09, -1.82]; Std. beta = -0.55, 95% CI [-0.70, -0.41])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.31, S.E. = 0.45, p < .001, 95% CI [-4.18, -2.44]; Std. beta = -0.75, 95% CI [-0.94, -0.55])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.05, S.E. = 0.49, p < .001, 95% CI [-4.01, -2.10]; Std. beta = -0.69, 95% CI [-0.91, -0.47])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.56, S.E. = 0.66, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.85, -1.27]; Std. beta = -0.58, 95% CI [-0.87, -0.29])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
